76561197992725681,Recommended,295590,22170103,"Posted: 31 March, 2016",all,Jaklyman,"Overall I had quite a lot of fun with Hero Generations. It's what it says on the label: A fun strategy roguelike. It has a solid tutorial and the core gameplay is easy to learn hard to master. Traits randomly passing down from both parents is an interesting mechanic and forces you to try and woo the best mate each generation. Also, buildings are named after their builder and age which gives the feeling that time is actually passing.Unfortunately though once you do master it you will quickly find that it isnt balanced particularly well. By the 3 hour mark I had found a way to cheese the game and become a 1000s of years old vampire living off the drained lifeforce of other adventurers. Kinda arguable who the real villian is in the game at that point. There are also a few glitches that still remain in the game that at this point I'm assuming are there to stay, they are not game breaking though so not a huge deal. Despite these negatives it was still quite a bit of fun for around 5 hours, but once you've killed and done everything there really doesn't feel like any reason to start again.TLDR: A simple but deep strategy roguelike that despite a few balance issues and glitches still managed to keep me entertained for around 5 hours, definitely recommend it to anyone who likes strategy games and roguelikes."
